english:
  title: A Record of Tae-an County
  author: Shin Suk-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The state established the garrison at Sunch'ŏng, which is now governed by the County Magistrate. The county possesses fertile lands abundant in grain and hemp, with rich harvests from fishing and salt—a region of true plenty. In the twilight of the former dynasty, it endured repeated ravages of war, becoming a wilderness of thorns where foxes and tigers roamed. Yet since our state arose in fortune, spreading benevolence and authority far and wide, the sea bandits have vanished like shadows. Thereafter, the scattered people returned to their homes, and those from other regions without dwelling places also gladly settled here. In the year Mushin, the court issued an edict to all provinces to register those who had fled and restore them to their original homes. Thus one hundred and four households of county people were recalled, but having long established their livelihoods here, relocation proved as difficult as settling in a new land.

    The current magistrate, the Concurrent Inspector Park Hongmun of Chuksan, has governed this place for four years. Reflecting deeply, he declared: "Our county has merely two hundred households. Those who render taxes and fulfill obligations are largely refugees and sojourners. They came because they found no peace elsewhere, yet now they dwell, marry, raise children and grandchildren here, each harboring plans to settle forever. How can we disturb them again? Moreover, a county exists for its people—without people, there is no county. We established this garrison to repel bandits—without people, who would defend it? This matter cannot remain unspoken to the throne." He then commanded the head elder to dispatch the county's former deputy official Lee Suk and elder Ga Taek to present his petition to the central government. Thus this one region alone received the blessing of stability.

    Therefore, from the youngest child to the eldest elder, all cried out in joy, singing: "When I shivered in cold, our lord wrapped me in warmth. When I was but skin and bone, our lord gave me flesh. When I wandered lost, our lord made me whole. When I trembled in fear, our lord granted me peace. To repay such virtue—is he not as my father and mother? Let his noble deeds be painted clear, to echo through all time."

    They approached the magistrate seeking that his deeds be recorded for posterity, but he demurred and refused. Yet knowing his steadfast refusal could not forever contain their will, they journeyed to the capital and sought me at the Jiphyŏnjŏn, requesting that I record these events for eternal remembrance. Their words and sentiments were deeply sincere. Though my brush is humble and I hold only a modest post in the historical bureau, recording virtue and vice is my office's charge. How much more so, when I have long known Magistrate Park, and his deeds prove so worthy of the written word?

    Magistrate Park is a man of integrity and gentle disposition, skilled in martial arts and versed in statecraft. Having served in both civilian and military posts, he has governed both people and armies with honor. Wherever he has gone, his incorruptibility, fairness, authority, and benevolence have earned him renown. Now governing both people and garrison, he unites civil and military affairs in one person, steadfastly devoted to the settlement and enrichment of his county. When the court pressed all administrators to return refugees within strict deadlines, many feared punishment and hastened to comply without reflection. Yet Magistrate Park alone had the wisdom to petition the throne, ultimately achieving his purpose. Thus the county gained substance, the garrison grew strong, and the people found peace in their homes. Such a magistrate truly honors the state's trust and embodies the way of a father and mother to the people.

    I have observed that the ancients, when moved by virtue shown to the people, would erect steles and sometimes build living temples—all springing from hearts that could not cease their admiration. How could I refuse a petition so earnest? Thus I write this record to send back to them. Let your people carve it upon wood and mount it upon the wall, that this county's descendants may forever know Magistrate Park's virtue and never forget it. At this point, even the magistrate himself has no words with which to refuse.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Sunch''ŏng garrison (蓴城鎭): A military fortification established to defend against maritime raids'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mushin year: Likely referring to 1448 in the Korean calendar, during the reign of King Sejong or his successor'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jiphyŏnjŏn (集賢殿): The Hall of Worthies, a prestigious government institution responsible for historical records and scholarly affairs'
  - key: ''
    value: The folk song quoted represents the common people's gratitude, using traditional poetic imagery of warmth, nourishment, and security as metaphors for good governance
